function forwardDiff = DerivativeApprox(measuredTemperature, sampleTime)
    % measuredTemperature: Engine temperature measurements in Celsius
    % sampleTime: Time the sample was collected in seconds

    % Assign forwardDiff with the forward difference approximation
    forwardDiff = diff(measuredTemperature) ./ diff(sampleTime);
end
```

In this code, the `diff` function is used to calculate the difference between consecutive elements in the `measuredTemperature` and `sampleTime` arrays. The element-wise division operator `./` is then used to perform element-wise division between the differences in `measuredTemperature` and `sampleTime`. This gives the forward difference approximation for the derivative at each point.

You can now call the `DerivativeApprox` function with the `measuredTemperature` and `sampleTime` arrays as arguments. For example:

```matlab
measuredTemperature = [91; 92; 94; 97];
sampleTime = [0; 1; 2; 3];
forwardDiff = DerivativeApprox(measuredTemperature, sampleTime);
disp(forwardDiff);
```

This will give you the `forwardDiff` array, which represents the forward difference approximation of the derivative of `measuredTemperature` with respect to `sampleTime`. In the provided example, the output will be `[1; 2; 3]`.
